I have to admit that I thought I had s=
een the worst &#39;paranormal&#39; show on television already. I was wrong. Door to=
 the Dead has exceeded my worst expectations.



Generally, I respect John=
 Oliver&#39;s work as a medium. While I have no personal experience with him, i=
n the past he has looked and acted more genuine than not, the rolling of th=
e eyes put aside for the moment.



I do take exception to the characteriz=
ation of the talking box as an Edison device. I have documented the history=
 of Edison, ITC and EVP  [http://www.sdparanormal.com/EdisonWhitePaper.html=
] elsewhere. This is however the smallest concern I have with this show.

 =


Prior to wathcing I had just had a conversation with a respected colleagu=
e on the West coast regarding interesting phenomena he and others are const=
antly observing in sites with phenomena similar to that on Door to the Dead=
. None of those measurements were made by this team. The use of thermal in =
this situation is not indicated as well.



The real concern is that no at=
tempt was made to help this family in a broader context. The skeptic did an=
d said nothing skeptical as far as I could tell. Key questions were not ask=
ed (at least on-camera) that would reveal the psycho-dynamics of this famil=
y. We know fairly well at this time that PK phenomena is often centered on =
a focal person who can exhibit specific characteristics. That the team seem=
s unaware of this is quite disturbing to a person like myself.



A real r=
esearch opportunity was lost in this case, as was an opportunity to educate=
 the public on the right way to approach such situations. Continually sendi=
ng the messages that phenomena is based on &#39;demons&#39; and &#39;spirits&#39; exclusive=
ly does nothing to further the position of serious investigators, which is =
perhaps most troubling of all.











